{{redirect|Pagania}}[[File:Neretva9st.png|thumb|right|300px|Narentine State or Pagania in the 9th century, according to [[De Administrando Imperio]].]] The '''Narentines''' were a [[South Slavs|South Slavic]]{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=306}} tribe that occupied an area of southern [[Dalmatia]] centered at the river [[Neretva]] ({{lang|la|Narenta}}), active in the 9th and 10th centuries, noted as pirates on the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]]. Named ''Narentani'' in Venetian sources, Greek sources call them ''Paganoi'', "pagans", as they were for long pagan, in a time when neighbouring tribes were Christianized. The tribe were fierce enemies of the [[Republic of Venice]], having attacked Venetian merchants and clergy passing on the Adriatic, and even raided close to [[Venice]] itself, as well as defeated the Doge several times. Venetian–Narentine peace treaties did not last long, as the Narentines quickly returned to piracy. They were finally defeated in a Venetian crackdown at the turn of the 10th century and disappeared from sources by the 11th century.
==Terminology== The word ''Narentine'' is a [[demonym]] derived from the local [[Neretva river]] ({{lang-lat|Narenta}}). The terms "Narentines", "Pagania" or "Pagans" are found in two contemporary sources: ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' ({{abbr|DAI|De Administrando Imperio}}), a mid-10th century Greek work, and ''[[Chronicon Venetum et Gradense]]'', a [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] chronicle by [[John the Deacon (Venetian chronicler)|John the Deacon]] from the early 11th century.{{sfn|Ančić|2011|p=255}}{{sfn|Živković|2012b|pp=11–12}} In ''De Administrando Imperio'' of Byzantine emperor [[Constantine VII|Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus]] (r. 913–959), the tribe is called ''Paganoi'' ({{lang-gr|Παγανοὶ, Παγανοἰ}}), and their polity ''Pagania'' (Παγανὶα, Παγανἰα), in Greek, while also noting that in Latin they are called ''Arentanoi'' (Αρεντανοἰ) and their polity ''Arenta'' (Αρεντα).{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|pp=152, 164–165}} Chronicler John the Deacon used the geographical term ''Narentani'' (as in ''princeps Narentanorum'',{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=62}} ''Narrentanos Sclavos''{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=39}}). In Serbo-Croatian, the tribal name is rendered as ''Neretljani'' (Неретљани) and ''Pagani'' (Пагани), while the polity mostly as ''Paganija'' (Паганија).
==Geography and economy== In DAI's chapters ''Story of the province of Dalmatia'' and ''Of the Pagani, also called Arentani, and of the country they now dwell in'', the geography of Pagania is described. Pagania had the counties (''[[župa|župa (zoupanias)]]'') of Rhastotza, Mokros and Dalen.{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=145}} Rhastotza and Mokros lay by the coast, and had galleys, while Dalen was distant from the sea and was based on agriculture.{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=145}} Pagania had the inhabited cities of Mokron ([[Makarska]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), Beroullia (presumably [[Brela]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), Ostrok ([[Zaostrog]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}) and Slavinetza (near [[Gradac, Split-Dalmatia County|Gradac]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), and the large islands of Kourkra/Kiker with a city ([[Korčula]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), Meleta/Malozeatai ([[Mljet]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), Phara ([[Hvar]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}) and Bratzis ([[Brač]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}).{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=165}} The Pagani raised flocks on the islands.{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=145}} Islands in the vicinity but not part of Pagania were Chora (presumably [[Sušac]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}), Iës ([[Vis (island)|Vis]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}) and Lastobon ([[Lastovo]]{{sfn|Institut za hrvatsku povijest|1974|p=29}}).{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=165}} Croatia was situated to the west, and [[Zachumlia]] to the east; Serbia was situated inland to the north, behind Pagania, Zachumlia, [[Travunija|Travunia]] and [[Duklja|Dioklea]], and bordered to Croatia on the Tzentina ([[Cetina]]) river.{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967|p=145}}
==History==
The ''[[Sclaveni]]'' (South Slavs) overwhelmed the Balkans in the 6th century. The ''DAI'' speaks of the Narentines as descended from the "unbaptized Serbs" that settled Dalmatia under the protection of Byzantine Emperor [[Heraclius]] (r. 610–641), and that the land of the Narentines had earlier been devastated by the Avars.{{sfn|Moravcsik|1967}} In 639 AD, ''[[Narona]]'', until then a flourishing Roman city, was destroyed by a horde of [[Pannonian Avars|Avars]] and Slavs.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=363}} A few years later, Slavic tribes took control of the lower Neretva.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=363}} The Slavs built a new town on the ruins of Narona, and erected a monument to their Slavic god [[Svetovid]], on the ruins of Roman temples.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=363}} According to Evans, ''Narentia'' became a stronghold for pagans in the Balkans, similarly to [[Balto-Slavs]] in [[Rügen]] (at [[Jaromarsburg]]).{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=363}} In 642, Slavs invaded southern Italy and attacked [[Siponto]], by ship from the Dalmatian coast.<ref name=C2001-PSD-N2009-3>{{harvnb|Ćorović|2001|loc=ch. "Prva srpska država"}}; {{harvnb|Narayan|2009|p=3}}</ref> Slavic naval raids on the Adriatic increased and it became unsafe for travel.<ref name=C2001-PSD-N2009-3/>
The first conflicts between the Venetians and Narentines came immediately before 830, around which time the first peace agreement was signed between the two (the Venetian Doge and ''Sclavorum de insula Narrentis'').{{sfn|Filozofski fakultet|1964|p=147}} Narentine Slavs sent envoys to Doge [[Giovanni I Participazio]] (r. 829–836).{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=37}} P. Skok believes this period also being the first contact between Venice and the middle Dalmatian islands.{{sfn|Filozofski fakultet|1964|p=147}} According to [[Pavel Jozef Šafárik|Šafárik]] (1795–1861), by the beginning of the 9th century their power had increased so much that Doge Giovanni I attacked them and then offered them peace.{{sfn|Kostić|1963|p=23}} The [[Republic of Venice]] was ''de facto'' subordinate the [[Byzantine Empire]], a period in which Venice expanded its trade relations towards the East.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=321}} In the first half of the 9th century Byzantium was struck by internal unrest, while the Bulgars and Arabs strengthened themselves thanks to this.<ref name=C2001-PSD>{{harvnb|Ćorović|2001|loc=ch. "Prva srpska država"}}</ref> Arabs took Crete in 825, Palermo in 831, Taranto in 839, then after destroying the Venetian navy by 840, they roamed freely in the Adriatic.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> In 841 Arabic ships attacked Adriatic cities and reached a confluence of the Padua river, while smaller contingents attacked [[Budva]], Roza and Lower [[Kotor]].<ref name=C2001-PSD/> In 842 the Arabs conquered Bari, and in 846 reached Rome itself.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> The Venetian navy, obliged to defend the Byzantine Adriatic, were occupied almost fully with battles with the Arabs.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> The Byzantine navy rarely appeared, and with small numbers of ships.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> This, and Arab harassment, gave the Slavic pirates around the Neretva upswing to develop their ship capabilities.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> When the Venetian navy was in Sicilian waters as guards in 827–828, the Narentines received momentum; when the Venetian navy returned, they calmed down.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> Venetian chronicles speak of a Narentine leader having been baptized in Venice, for greater security for the latter; however, the Narentines are unsteady and deceptive as their sea; as soon as events in Venice or the Adriatic worsen, the Narentines continued their piracy.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> One of their attacks in 834–835, when they robbed and killed some Venetian merchants returning from Benevento, caused great resentment against them in Venice.<ref name=C2001-PSD/>
In order to stop these assaults, the Venetians undertook a large expedition against the Dalmatian Slavic pirates in 839.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> Doge [[Pietro Tradonico]] sent warships against the Slavic lands (''Sclavenia'').{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=37}} According to [[Ferdo Šišić|F. Šišić]] Doge Pietro ordered an attack on the Narentines in the spring of 839.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=328}} According to [[Vjekoslav Klaić|V. Klaić]], Tradonico had first defeated and made peace with the Croats under Mislav, then proceeded to attack the Narentine islands and make peace with Narentine leader Drosaico.{{sfn|Klaić|1972|p=73}} There are no information on the fights that year, but it is known that peace was concluded with Croats and a part of the Narentines.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> Venetian chronicler [[John the Deacon (Venetian chronicler)|John the Deacon]] (1008) records a renewal of the peace treaty signed by Drosaico (''ad Narrentanas insulas cum Drosaico, Marianorum iudice, similiter fedus instituit'').{{sfn|Klaić|1971|p=217}} The peace with the Narentines did not last long, perhaps as the Narentines signed it to avoid danger, or more likely because it was not concluded with all, but a tribe or clan of the Narentines.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> In 840 the Venetians attacked Narentine leader Ljudislav, ending in failure;<ref name=C2001-PSD/> Ljudislav (''Liuditus sclavus''), possibly a successor or co-ruler of Drosaico, defeated the Venetian Doge and killed hundreds of his men.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=328}} According to Klaić it was the Narentines who broke the peace.{{sfn|Klaić|1972|p=73}} It seems that Narentine piracy even reached Istria by February 840.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=328}} The [[840 Venetian–Frankish treaty]] included common fight against Slavic tribes (''generationes Sclavorum inimicas'').{{sfn|Fine|2006|pp=37–38}} After two defeats to the Venetian navy by the Arabs immediately after, the Venetians were unable to enter new fights with the Dalmatian Slavs.<ref name=C2001-PSD/> In 846 the Narentines reached close to Venice itself, and raided nearby [[Caorle]].<ref name=C2001-PSD/>{{sfn|Narayan|2009|p=4}} [[File:Map of the Western Balkans around 814 AD.png|left|thumb|Western Balkan polities in the early 9th century.]] The arrival of [[Basil I]] (r. 867–886) to the Byzantine throne led to important changes in Byzantium; energetic, he managed to enter closer ties with Bulgars, and even the distant Croats, and protected the Empire well.<ref name=C2001-PJS>{{harvnb|Ćorović|2001|loc=ch. "Pokrštavanje Južnih Slovena"}}</ref> When [[Dubrovnik|Ragusa (Dubrovnik)]] asked for the emperor's help against the threat of the [[Saracens]], he dispatched a strong navy into the Adriatic.<ref name=C2001-PJS/> Byzantine admiral [[Niketas Ooryphas]] took up closer contacts with the Serb tribes around Ragusa, the [[Zahumlje|Zachumlians]], [[Travunija|Travunians]] and [[Konavle|Konavlians]], and invited them to jointly combat the Saracens, both on land and sea, in 869.<ref name=C2001-PJS/> Only Slavic tribes of southern Dalmatia were called to cooperate; to the north, the Croats and Dalmatians entered relations with Italian king [[Louis II of Italy|Louis]] at the dismay of the Byzantines.<ref name=C2001-PJS/> When some "Slavs"<ref name=C2001-PJS/> (Narentines according to Narayan{{sfn|Narayan|2009|p=4}}) in March 870 kidnapped the [[Bishop of Rome]]'s emissaries returning home from the [[Fourth Council of Constantinople (Roman Catholic)|Fourth Council]] in [[Constantinople]],{{sfn|Narayan|2009|p=4}} the Byzantines used this as a good pretext to attack and force them into submission (871).<ref name=C2001-PJS/> The ''DAI'' mentions that the Narentines were called "pagans, because they did not accept baptism in the time when all Serbs were baptized", which is placed during Basil's rule.<ref name=C2001-PJS/> The Narentines are not mentioned in relation to the Byzantine military expedition on Bari dispatched by [[Basil I]] (r. 867–886), in which other Dalmatian Slavs participated.{{sfn|Vizantološki institut|1997|p=15}} The Croats, Serbs, Zachlumians, Travunians, Konavlians, Ragusans, "with all the men of the towns of Dalmatia", crossed over the sea to [[Longobardia|Langobardia]] and took Bari.{{sfn|Živković|2008|p=165}} Basil returned [[Dalmatia (theme)|Dalmatia under Byzantine rule]]{{sfn|Vizantološki institut|1997|p=15}} by 878, and a large part of Dalmatia was put under the [[Patriarchate of Constantinople]].<ref name=C2001-PJS/> The ''DAI'' claims that the Dalmatian Slavs asked Basil I to baptize them; the Christianization of the Narentines seems to have failed.{{sfn|Vizantološki institut|1997|p=15}} According to Evans, the Narentines remained pagan until 873, when Byzantine admiral Ooryphas persuaded them to accept baptism.{{sfn|Evans|2007|p=363}} While Doge [[Orso I Participazio]] and his son [[Giovanni II Participazio]] made peace and an alliance with the Croats after 876, the Venetians were still at war with the Narentines.{{sfn|Klaić|1972|p=80}}
In 880 the Venetian–Frankish treaty was renewed.{{sfn|Brković|2001|p=32}} In 887 Doge [[Pietro I Candiano]] sent troops against the Narentine Slavs, landing at the "Slavic Hill" (''mons Sclavorum''), putting the Slavs to flight.{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=37}} The Narentines were defeated in a battle in August 887 at Makarska, and their five ships were destroyed with axes.{{sfn|Brković|2001|p=32}} With help from neighbours, the Narentines decisively defeated the Venetian navy on 18 September 887, with the Doge killed in action and his body left laying (Andrea Tribun later secretly took the body to Venice).{{sfn|Brković|2001|p=32}} From this time until 948 the Venetian chronicles do not mention conflicts with the Croats, which would mean that the Venetians offered peace and paid tribute to the Croats.{{sfn|Brković|2001|p=32}}
Pagania was by the reign of Serbian ruler [[Petar Gojniković]] (r. 892–917) part of the [[Principality of Serbia (medieval)|Serbian principality]]. Petar and the Byzantine commander of [[Dyrrhachium (theme)|Dyrrhachion]] [[Leo Rhabdouchos]] met in Narentine lands regarding an alliance against the Bulgars.<ref name=C2001-SiVHB>{{harvnb|Ćorović|2001|loc=ch. "Srbi između Vizantije, Hrvatske i Bugarske"}}</ref> [[Michael of Zahumlje]], who had been pushed out from Zahumlje to the neighbouring islands by Petar, informed the Bulgars about these negotiations.<ref name=C2001-SiVHB/> In 917 Petar was tricked by the Bulgars, who then annexed Serbia in 924–927,{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=153}} until [[Časlav]] returned to Serbia and rebuilt the state, in Byzantine alliance.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=159}} Časlav's state included Pagania (the Narentines).{{cn|date=June 2016}} In the 940s, the islands of [[Brač]] and [[Hvar]], which had earlier become part of the [[Kingdom of Croatia (925–1102)|Croatian kingdom]], seceded during Ban [[Pribina, Ban of Croatia|Pribina]]'s rebellion and rejoined the Narentine province.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=436}} The Narentines took advantage of the internal unrest in Croatia after the death of [[Petar Krešimir]] (945) and took the islands of [[Sušac|Cazza]], [[Vis (island)|Vis]] and [[Lastovo]].<ref name=C2001-SiVHB/> In 948 the Narentines were at war with Venetian Doge [[Pietro III Candiano]], who sent 33 war galleys under Urso Badovario and Pietro Rozollo; the Narentines managed to defend themselves.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=436}} The Venetians were forced to pay tribute to the Narentines for safe sea passage.<ref name=C2001-SiVHB/> Serbia collapsed after Časlav's death in ca. 960, into smaller units.<ref name=C2001-SiVHB/>
In 997, the Narentines increased raids against Latin and Venetian towns, and they had close ties with Croat ruler [[Svetoslav Suronja]], who at the time fought his two brothers over the throne; this relation caused the Latin Dalmatian towns and Venice to turn against Svetoslav.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=274}} In 998, the Republic of Venice, under the Byzantine Emperor, exerted control over the Byzantine Dalmatian towns; Dalmatian Croatia was in civil war; the Narentines were semi-independent, raiding the Adriatic, particularly against Venice.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=276}} As Venice gained authority in Dalmatia, some Dalmatian towns that felt threatened allied with the Narentines.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=276}} The Venetians then interved and defeated the Narentines and their Croatian allies decisively on sea, resulting in Narentine power decline.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=276}}
On 9 May 1000, Venetian Doge [[Pietro II Orseolo]]<ref>Lane, Frederic Chapin. ''Venice, a Maritime Republic'', p. 26</ref> decided to conquer the allied Croats and Narentines, protecting the interests of their trading colonies and the Latin Dalmatian citizenry. Without difficulty, he struck the entire eastern Adriatic coastline - with only the Narentines offering him some resistance. As a counterattack, the Narentines kidnapped 40 of the foremost citizens of [[Zadar|Zara (Zadar)]] and stole a transport of goods from [[Apulia]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} On their way home, Pietro II dispatched 10 ships that surprised them between Lastovo and Kača and took them as prisoners to [[Trogir]]. Narentine emissaries came to the Doge's temporary residence at [[Split (city)|Split]] (Spalato) to beg for the release of the prisoners. They guaranteed that the Narentine prince himself would show up with his men and renounce the old rights to tax the Venetians for free passage. All prisoners were allowed to return to their homes, except for six that were kept as hostages. Lastovo and Korčula continued to oppose the Venetians. Korčula was conquered by Pietro II and Lastovo fell too after long bloody fights. As Lastovo was very infamous in the Venetian world for being a pirate haven, the Doge ordered it to be evacuated in order to be razed. After the denizens of Lastovo refused to concur, the Venetians attacked and razed it to the ground.
==Leaders== *''Drosaico'' (Drosaik, Dražko, Draško), Venetian chronicler [[John the Deacon (Venetian chronicler)|John the Deacon]]<ref name="Dümmler1856">{{cite book|author=Ernst Dümmler|title=Über die älteste Geschichte der Slaven in Dalmatien: (549-928)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S7AAAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA45|year=1856|publisher=Braumüller in Komm.|pages=45–}}</ref> (1008) records a renewal of Venetian–Narentine peace treaty signed by Drosaico (''Ad Narrantanas insulas cum Drosaico, Marianorum iudice, similiter fedus instituit'').<ref>{{cite book|title=Atti e memorie della Società dalmata di storia patria|volume=7–9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pE5QAQAAIAAJ|year=1970|publisher=La Società|p=119}}</ref> *''Liuditus sclavus'' (Ljudislav), possibly a successor or co-ruler of Drosaico, defeated the Venetian Doge and killed hundreds of his men.{{sfn|Šišić|1990|p=328}} *''Unusclavus'' and ''Diodurus''<!--Unuslavus, ac Diodorus--> were according to [[Johann Christian von Engel]] (1798)<ref name="Engel1798">{{cite book|author=Johann Christian von Engel|title=Kroatien Slavonien|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JTNZAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA460|year=1798|publisher=Gebauer|page=460}}</ref> the leaders of the raid on Caorle (which took place in 846 according to Narayan{{sfn|Narayan|2009|p=4}}). [[Pavel Jozef Šafařík|Šafařík]] included the note in ''Slowanské Starožitnosti'' (1837), and rendered their names as "Uneslaw" and "Diodur".<ref name="Šafařík1837">{{cite book|author=Pavel Jozef Šafařík|title=Slowanské Starožitnosti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A5NeAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA657|year=1837|publisher=tiskem J. Spurného|pages=657–}}</ref> *''Berigui'' or ''Berigoy'' (Berigoj), mentioned in a 1050 charter of the Benedictine [[Abbey of Santa Maria a Mare|monastery of St Mary]] on the island of [[Isole Tremiti|Tremiti]] as a "king of the coastal people" (''rex marianorum''), then as a "judge of the coastal people" (''iudex Maranorum'').{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=62}}<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ildar H. Garipzanov|author2=Patrick J. Geary|author3=Przemysław Urbańczyk|title=Franks, Northmen, and Slavs: Identities and State Formation in Early Medieval Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4dUWAQAAIAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Isd|isbn=978-2-503-52615-7|p=235}}</ref>
==Legacy==
There is a historical festival called ''matrimonio'' in [[Venice]] commemorating the victory over the Narentines,<ref>{{cite book|author=Marcel Brion|title=Venice: The Masque of Italy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qHBoAAAAMAAJ|year=1962|publisher=Elek|p=63}}</ref> held on [[Candlemas]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Catholic World|volume=106–108|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LAkXAQAAIAAJ|year=1918|publisher=Paulist Fathers|p=365}}</ref>
==Historiography== The question of the ethnic designation of the tribe, whether it, apart from being Slavic, was to be described as Serb or Croat, is often found in historiography.{{sfn|Živković|2012b|p=12}} The earliest information about the Narentines is from the early 9th century, compiled in the ''Chronicon Venetum et Gradense''.{{sfn|Živković|2012b|p=13}} The Venetian chronicle used the Slavic ethnonym ({{lang-la|Narrentanos Sclavos}}) to refer to the Narentines.{{sfn|Fine|2006|pp=37, 39, 62}}
''De Administrando Imperio'' also gives information about the Narentines, originating from the 870s.{{sfn|Živković|2012b|p=13}} There, the Narentines are described as "descended from the unbaptized Serbs" ... The Pagans are so called because they did not accept baptism at the time when all the Serbs were baptized."{{sfn|Živković|2012|pp=194–195}} Romanian-American historian [[Florin Curta]] considered it "an indication that in the mid-tenth century the coastal zhupanias were under the control of the Serbian ''zhupan'' Časlav", as noted in his 2006 book.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=210}} Serbian historian [[Tibor Živković]] wrote in 2012 that "it was stated in the DAI that the Serbs had been baptized much earlier, and therefore, the Pagans could not have belonged to the Serb tribe. There is information in chapter 32, that the Serbs controlled Pagania in ca. 895, during the rule of the Archon Peter, and from this political situation Constantine would have been able to write that the Pagans belonged to the Serbian tribe."{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=195}} Croatian historian Neven Budak also holds that remarks regarding the Narentines were related to the political situation at the time.{{sfn|Budak|1994|p=58}}
In the ''[[Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja]]'', a work written by a Catholic bishop likely for a Croatian ruler in ca. 1300–10,<ref>{{citation|last1=Živković|first1=T.|last2=Kunčer|first2=D.|title=Gesta regum Sclavorum, I–II|location=Београд|year=2009|pages=362–365}}</ref> the southern Dalmatian principalities are referred to as part of "[[Red Croatia]]".{{sfn|Fine|2006|p=62}} While later parts of the ''Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja'' are considered of high value, events described in the early Middle Ages are largely discredited in historiography.{{sfn|Živković|2006|p=16}}
[[Pavel Jozef Šafárik]] (1795–1861) viewed that the first information on Serbs in history were from events regarding the Narentines.{{sfn|Kostić|1963|p=23}} [[Konstantin Josef Jireček]] (1854–1918) treated them as a distinct South Slavic tribe.<ref name=Zs49>{{cite book|title=Zadarska smotra|volume=49|issue=4–6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oJwTAQAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Matica hrvatska|p=567}}</ref> Croatian historian [[Ferdo Šišić|F. Šišić]] (1869–1940) said that the Neretva population were "ever and always fully identical to the Croat [population], including also its [[Chakavian]] dialect" (1952).<ref name=Zs49/> Croatian historian [[Vladimir Košćak]] (1921–1991) believed that the Narentines were under Croat rule from [[Trpimir I of Croatia|Trpimir]] until [[Domagoj of Croatia|Domagoj]] (d. 876), and that after the latter's death, they sent emissaries to Basil I and recognized his rule, which was however short-lived as spanning only to the fall of Byzantine [[:wikt:protégé|protégé]] [[Zdeslav of Croatia|Zdeslav]] (879) when the Narentines again fell away from Byzantium; Košćak wanted to reduce Byzantine rule also to the south of Pagania, claiming that the provinces of Pagania, Zachumlia, Travunia and Duklja again came under Croat rule during [[Branimir of Croatia|Branimir]] (r. 879–892).{{sfn|Vizantološki institut|1997|p=16}} This theory was criticized by the Serbian academic [http://www.byzinst-sasa.rs/eng/ Institute for Byzantine Studies].{{sfn|Vizantološki institut|1997|p=16}} Serbian historiography in the 19th and 20th century considered the Narentines to be Serbs.{{sfn|Ančić|2011|p=224}} [[Vladimir Ćorović]] (1885–1941) treated the Narentines as the first of the Serb tribes to take the initiative of fighting, not for defence and tribal organization, but for the liberty of selfish desires and security raids.<ref name=C2001-PSD/>
According to Croatian historian [[Ivo Goldstein]], the Narentines "could not be regarder neither Serbs nor Croats."{{sfn|Goldstein|1995|p=196}} Budak wrote that the Narentines were "undoubtedly a distinct ethnic group", who "disappeared as a separate ethnicity when their principality was joined into Croatia".{{sfn|Budak|1994|p=59}}
