'''Simen Skappel''' (7 March 1866 – 15 July 1945) was a [[Norwegian people|Norwegian]] [[historian]] and [[statistician]].

He specialized in agricultural history and agricultural statistics, and worked for [[Statistics Norway]] for 34 years, leading the Department of agricultural statistics for parts of that period.<ref name=obit>{{cite news|title=Dødsfall|date=20 July 1945|work=Verdens gang|page=6|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He was hired in Statistics Norway in 1902, was promoted to secretary in 1911 and department head in 1928.<ref name=arbleks>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1936|volume=6|title=Skappel, Simen|encyclopedia=[[Arbeidernes Leksikon]]|editor1=[[Jakob Friis|Friis, Jakob]] |editor2=[[Trond Hegna|Hegna, Trond]] |editor3=[[Dagfin Juel|Juel, Dagfin]] |publisher=Arbeidermagasinets Forlag|location=Oslo|language=Norwegian|page=299}}</ref> His most prominent publication was ''Om husmannsvesenet i Norge'', published in 1922.<ref name=obit/> A ''husmann'' in Norway was a type of [[Croft (land)|crofter]]. In the book, Skappel distinguished between [[Croft (land)|crofters]] who received some land in exchange for work, often on short-term contracts, and crofters who received land in exchange for rent, often on lifetime contracts. Skappel's theory has been discussed as late as around 2000, but has been found (by historian [[Ståle Dyrvik]]) models to lack important complexity.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dyrvik|first=Ståle|authorlink=Ståle Dyrvik|title=Norsk historie 1625–1814|publisher=Samlaget|location=Oslo|date=1999|series=Volume three of ''[[Norsk historie (Samlaget)|Norsk historie]]''|pages=132, 136|isbn=978-82-521-5546-4|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Other prominent works by Skappel include ''Hedemarkens amt 1814–1914'' and ''Ringsaker Sparebank 1847–1927'', but he mostly published in journals. He died in the summer of 1945.<ref name=obit/>

